title: Grateful Dead Live at Fillmore West on 1970-06-06
description:
Set 1

Don't Ease Me In, The Frozen Logger, Friend Of The Devil, Candyman, Deep Elem Blues, Cumberland Blues, Wake Up Little Susie, New Speedway Boogie

Set 2

Morning Dew, Me & My Uncle, Casey Jones, Dancin' In The Streets, Next Time You See Me, China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Good Lovin'-> Drums-> New Orleans-> Good Lovin', Attics Of My Life, Dire Wolf, Alligator-> Drums-> Turn On Your Love Light-> Not Fade Away-> Turn On Your Love Light-> Uncle John's Band

Other artist(s): GD; NRPS; Southern Comfort first set acoustic

reviews.review_text: Thank you Thank you! Incredible that this stuff continues to surface, 45 years after the fact.

Lovelight This is a great stretched out version with the band getting into all kinds of unique grooves.  The Fillmore West at this time seems to have been a place where the band felt they could relax and try new things. The Not Fade Away sandwiched in towards the end isn't as menacing as, say, 5-6-70 Kresge Plaza, but it's certainly "of that time" and packs a punch.

The Dew is also nice (love the sound of Pigpen plugging in the organ!) and, as others have noted, the Alligator jam is quite different from the jam heard the previous year (and earlier).

The Dancin' is tight.  A lot of times the "tighten up" jam kinda kills the song's momentum for me but the band segues into it here pretty quickly and smoothly.  This version may be the exception that proves the rule ...? Superb drumming and the sound quality is magnificent.

at one point In Pigpens rap in Lovelight
he sounds exactly like Janis Joplin.
like male and female versions of the
same cosmic power
- Although the first half or so is nothing that special, Alligator & everything after is so smokin' I can't stand it.
Next time you see me... ...Things won't be the same.
